### The Pillars of ESG: What They Actually Measure

ESG has been adopted across the US financial industry as a means to evaluate the [sustainability](/Sustainability) and societal impact of a company or [business](/Business). [MSCI](/MSCI), a prominent ESG [rating agency](/Rating_agency), defines ESG investing as the integration of environmental, social, and governance factors alongside financial considerations in investment decisions. Similarly, [S&P](/S%26P_Global_Ratings) emphasizes how environmental, social, and governance risks and opportunities can materially affect a company's performance.

*   **Environmental Aspect:** This encompasses data related to [climate change](/Climate_change), [greenhouse gas emissions](/Greenhouse_gas_emissions), [biodiversity loss](/Biodiversity_loss), [deforestation](/Deforestation)/[reforestation](/Reforestation), pollution control, [energy efficiency](/Efficient_energy_use), and [water management](/Water_management).
*   **Social Aspect:** This focuses on how companies interact with their employees and communities. It includes metrics on employee safety and health, [working conditions](/Working_conditions), [diversity, equity, and inclusion](/Diversity,_equity,_and_inclusion), and responses to conflicts and humanitarian crises. Crucially, effective social practices can enhance [customer satisfaction](/Customer_satisfaction) and [employee engagement](/Employee_engagement), directly impacting risk and return assessments.
*   **Governance Aspect:** This delves into the internal structures and processes that guide and control companies. It covers issues such as [preventing bribery](/Anti-bribery) and [corruption](/Anti-corruption), the diversity of the Board of Directors, [executive compensation](/Executive_compensation), [cybersecurity](/Cybersecurity) and [privacy](/Privacy) protocols, and the overall management structure.

